'''Level 480''', also known as “M1DNIGHT” is designated the 481<sup>st</sup> level of the Backrooms…
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<div style="text-align:center"><div style="background: #808080; color: #FFFFFF; margin:1em; padding:5px 10px; border:4px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 32px; font-size: 32px"><center><span style="font-family:Trajan Pro;">Description</span></center>
</div> </div>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<span style="font-family:Chiller;">
{{Blurimage|file=480-1.jpg|caption=The most famous photo of '''Level 480'''.}}
'''Level 480''' presents itself as an unnaturally flat landscape dotted with many parts of common infrastructure, such as roads, bridges, and buildings. The time on '''Level 480''' is entirely locked in a state of '''M1DN1GHT''', with no moon and natural stars in the sky. Throughout '''Level 480''', there are many lights illuminating the space in front of the many roads and buildings. Most of '''Level 480''' does not contain these lights, resulting in pitch black areas due to the lack of light. The temperature within '''Level 480''' can be very cold at times, but it mainly stays at approximately 60 to 68 degrees Fahrenheit (15.5 to 20 degrees Celsius).

Most of '''Level 480’s''' roads are erratic and take complex and convoluted routes that would normally not be useful or connect anywhere. The roads are capable of branching, turning, or halting unexpectedly. The roads themselves also harbor very unnatural oddities, such as turning 180 degrees upside down or going up at a 90-degree angle. Despite '''Level 480''' appearing to have no true non-Euclidean geometry, the roads can change abruptly when one looks away from an area, making navigation throughout '''Level 480''' very difficult.
{{Blurimage|file=480.2.jpg|caption=Another famous photo of '''Level 480'''.}}
Buildings surrounding '''Level 480’s''' roads can vary wildly, from small shacks to large gas stations and rest stops. These buildings are usually always lit, and appears to be in a mostly pristine, but abandoned state, as if the town’s residents left quickly. The interior of said buildings appears to be almost completely empty, save for a couple pieces of furniture and a couple snacks and bottles of [[Almond Water]]. All electronics within the stores also seem to be mostly functional, aside from some buffering on the displays.

Radio connections seem to mostly lose signal upon entering '''Level 480''', except for a small sliver that is capable of exiting '''Level 480''' entirely and reaching external connections. Currently, it is unknown what causes connections to be intercepted, but it is theorized that either an entity prevents radio signals from coming through or that '''Level 480''' has a property of its own that blocks radio signals. Visual displays and cameras seem to have the same effect upon entering '''Level 480''', with the images being either unclear or mangled and jumbled. Fortunately, '''Level 480''' could be photographed from an interior camera already on the level, then transported to image displays and rendering once the subject leaves the level.
{{Blurimage|file=480-3.jpg|caption=Another photo of '''Level 480''' showcasing a road through a tunnel.}}
'''Level 480''' is presumed to be infinite in area, however, when one wanders too far into the level, they will hear an very loud sound mix of static and glitching, and visual static will enter one’s vision. Eventually, one will begin to feel a strong headache and dizziness. The symptoms will slowly increase in strength until the wanderer eventually passes out and wakes up back at the level's entry point. The distance where one begins to wander “too far” and feels the effects are widely varied, but it’s assumed to be around 2,600 to 11,000 mi (4200 to 17700 km) away from the initial entry point of '''Level 480'''.

A common occurrence on '''Level 480''' is the presence of slight time dilation. Time appears to move slower on '''Level 480''', meaning that everything, including one’s movements, is slowed down. However, in certain circumstances inside buildings, time appears to move at a normal rate or even speeds up on occasion. Foodstuffs on '''Level 480''' show no signs of decay, despite the ubiquitous passing of time. There have also been reports of time halting completely, but it is unconfirmed at the current moment.

Towns and communities are also scattered across '''Level 480''', but they are pretty rare to come across. Just like the individual buildings present in the level, the towns resemble an untouched pristine condition yet abandoned. Unlike individual buildings, however, buildings in a town or community possess many types of furniture and resources, including almond water, and are usually unlit, with the only exceptions being major convenience stores and storage units. Temperatures inside a town are also higher than the rest of '''Level 480''', being around 72 degrees Fahrenheit (21 degrees Celsius).

{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<div style="text-align:center"><div style="background: #808080; color: #FFFFFF; margin:1em; padding:5px 10px; border:4px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 32px; font-size: 32px"><center><span style="font-family:Trajan Pro;">Entities</span></center>
</div> </div>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

===Mannequins===
Mannequins, not to be confused with [[Entity 29]], are the only discovered entities on '''Level 480'''. Mannequins take the appearance of regular mannequins from [[The Frontrooms]], only that they bear an uncanny resemblance to regular human features when looked up closely, and they seemingly wear many types of clothes, including shirts, socks, and shoes. Mannequins themselves are capable of locomotion, but they usually only move when one blinks or looks away from them. Despite their uncanny nature, mannequins do not pose a serious threat within '''Level 480''', as they don’t usually attack wanderers unless provoked, although they are usually very curious and like to check out wanderers who come near one. It’s recommended to continually look at a mannequin and not blink until one is approximately two meters (6.5 feet) away. Although they are the only documented entity, mannequins are pretty rare within '''Level 480'''.

{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<div style="text-align:center"><div style="background: #808080; color: #FFFFFF; margin:1em; padding:5px 10px; border:4px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 32px; font-size: 32px"><center><span style="font-family:Trajan Pro;">Entrances and Exits</span></center>
</div> </div>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

===Entrances===
*Noclipping through an exterior door on [[Level 2]] will lead one here.
*Exiting out of any grocery store level has a chance to lead one here.
*Although it is not confirmed, it is possible that the environment of [[Level 690]] could transition into here over a long enough period.
*One could enter this level from [[Level 499]] by an unknown fashion.
*A metal door in [[Level 479]] will lead one here.
*Noclipping through a concrete wall on [[Level 511]] will lead one here.

===Exits===
*If one sees a bridge with a huge amount of fog around it, walking across it will lead one to [[Level 500]].
*The towns could slowly transition into [[Level 9]].
*Consuming pink cotton candy leads one to [[Level 9.2]].
*Entering a parking garage style structure will lead one to [[Level 1]].
*Noclipping into a car will lead one to [[Level 91]] after a long fall.
*Off-ramps marked with an archway with a sign reading "Kaleidoscope Studios" might lead to [[Level 979]].
